[2] Sudan vaccination
Date: Thu 23 Apr 2015
Source: Radio Dabanga [edited]
https://www.dabangasudan.org/en/all-news/article/nearly-8-million-children-in-sudan-to-be-vaccinated-against-measles


Nearly 8 million children in Sudan to be vaccinated against measles
-------------------------------------------------------------------
The Sudanese Ministry of Health, in cooperation with UNICEF and national partners, today [23 Apr 2015] launched a massive campaign to immunise 7.9 million children, aged 6 months to 15 years, against the life-threatening disease.

In one of the worst measles outbreaks in Sudan's recent history, which began in the end of 2014, there have been 1730 confirmed cases, 3175 suspected cases and 22 fatalities, UNICEF stated in a news note today.

Of the total number of reported measles cases, 69 per cent are below 15 years of age, including 52 per cent under the age of 5. West Darfur remains the worst affected state, with 441 confirmed cases and 5 deaths. Kassala has had 365 confirmed cases and 5 deaths, while in Red Sea state there have been 263 cases and 4 deaths.

"Measles is a life threatening disease, but one that can easily be prevented with timely immunisation," UNICEF representative in Sudan Geert Cappelaere said. Sudan has one of the highest levels of malnutrition in Africa. 36 per cent of the children are stunted, which is a primary manifestation of undernutrition. For malnourished children, measles can cause serious complications, including blindness, ear infections, pneumonia, and severe diarrhoea. "Every girl and boy must be reached, no matter where they live. There are no excuses and no child can be left out."

The campaign will initially target 28 affected localities in 6 of the highest risk states, before expanding to other areas identified as being at risk of an outbreak. In total 96 localities in 16 affected and "at risk" states will be targeted. There are children in conflict zones in South Kordofan, Blue Nile, and Darfur who have not received routine immunisation since 2011. UNICEF has called on the warring parties to facilitate humanitarian access, so that these children can be reached.

The campaign is expected to cost approximately USD 13.9 million. UNICEF is appealing to all donors to make funding available to fight the outbreak, which is having a detrimental effect on the lives of children across Sudan and threatens neighbouring countries. UNICEF, the World Health Organization (WHO), and partners are coordinating with surrounding countries to stop this outbreak from crossing the borders.

