[3] USA (Florida)
Date: Wed 22 Apr 20115
Source: Outbreak News Today [edited]
http://outbreaknewstoday.com/florida-4th-measles-case-confirmed-in-treasure-coast-79780/


Florida: 4th measles case confirmed in Treasure Coast
-----------------------------------------------------
The Florida Department of Health today [22 Apr 2015] confirmed a case of measles in an unvaccinated adolescent in Indian River County. The case has recovered. This brings the total cases of measles between Indian River and St Lucie counties to 4. Measles is a serious respiratory disease caused by a virus of the same name. The disease is highly contagious and can spread to others who are unvaccinated.

"Vaccination continues to be the best prevention against measles," said state surgeon general and secretary of health Dr John Armstrong. "Vaccination remains so important for children, adults and families across our state to protect themselves and their communities from this serious and preventable infection."

The department is working with community health care partners and encourages all residents and visitors who have not been immunized to get vaccinated immediately. Vaccinations are available year round through health departments in Florida's 67 counties or your local doctor's office.

People who are particularly susceptible are pregnant woman, infants under the age of 12 months and people who are immunocompromised. Measles is spread through the air by breathing, coughing or sneezing and is highly contagious. When a person sneezes or coughs, droplets spray into the air. The virus can live on surfaces or in an airspace where the infected person coughed or sneezed for up to 2 hours. It can be transmitted from 4 days before the rash becomes visible to 4 days after the rash appears. A typical case of measles begins with flu-like symptoms. The symptoms of measles generally begin approximately 7 to 14 days after a person is exposed to someone with measles.

